'''Michael Anthony Pegues''' (born May 11, 1962) is an [[African American]] [[visual artist]] living in New York City. Born and raised in Brooklyn, mother's family from Liberia, father's from Portugal, he attended alternative High School Redirection, [[Brownsville, Brooklyn]], and later [[Nassau Community College]], Garden City, LI.<ref name="brooklynartscouncil">{{cite web|url=http://www.brooklynartscouncil.org/registry/28925|title=Michael Anthony Pegues &#124; Brooklyn Arts Council|publisher=brooklynartscouncil.org|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref>  Self-taught, modern-day [[Fauvism|Fauve]], [[Expressionist]] as well as [[Pop artist]], contemporary of [[Andy Warhol]], [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]], [[Keith Haring]], his work is strongly influenced by [[Hip Hop]] and [[Graffiti]]. Pegues had his first major solo and retrospective show at the FB Gallery in New York in 2012, "Prince Michael’s Neverland: The Measure of an Artist: Michael Anthony Pegues," May 16 – June 3.<ref name="fbgallery">{{cite web|url=http://fbgallery.net/|title=http://fbgallery.net/|publisher=fbgallery.net|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref> His work was exhibited in Italy, his first solo show abroad, in 2014 at Le 4 Pareti: galleria d'arte, Napoli, April 5–17.<ref name="le4p">{{cite web|url=http://le4p.com/2014/03/27/michael-anthony-pegues-comunicato-stampa/|title=MICHAEL ANTHONY PEGUES &#8211; COMUNICATO STAMPA &#124;|publisher=le4p.com|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref>
His acrylic canvases, sculptures and assemblages have also been exhibited in New York at Aurora Gallery,<ref name="graffiti">{{cite web|url=http://www.graffiti.org/index/history2005.html|title=Art Crimes: Graffiti Shows and Events: 2005|publisher=graffiti.org|accessdate=2014-10-31|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141204113017/http://www.graffiti.org/index/history2005.html|archivedate=2014-12-04|df=}}</ref> Chelsea (under the graffiti tag Mazike), Jonathan Shorr Gallery, Soho, and the New York Public Library,<ref name="nypl">{{cite web|url=http://www.nypl.org/events/exhibitions/michael-pegues-children-world|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130601211032/http://www.nypl.org/events/exhibitions/michael-pegues-children-world |archive-date=2013-06-01 |dead-url=yes|title=Michael Pegues - Children of the World  &#124; The New York Public Library|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref> among other places.

He has collaborated with the artist Cinthus (aka Martin H.Leff-Cinthus)<ref name="cinth">{{cite web|url=http://cinth.us/|title=The Leff Gallery|publisher=cinth.us|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref> and the writer Tom Mathew, illustrating the latter's children's book ''The Magic Rug: A Christmas Story''<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=The Magic Rug: A Christmas Story|author1=Mathew, T.|author2=Pegues, M.A.|date=2010|publisher=Trademark Universal, Incorporated|isbn=9780615422633|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=u2dLYgEACAAJ|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref> (Staten Island, New York: Trademark Universal, Inc., 2010).

A prominent figure in the downtown art scene, he frequently attends gallery openings, receptions, fundraisers and other social functions, and has been photographed by the likes of nightlife photographer [[Patrick McMullan]],<ref name="patrickmcmullan">{{cite web|url=http://www.patrickmcmullan.com/site/search.aspx?t=person&s=Michael%20Anthony%20Pegues|title=Patrick McMullan Company|publisher=patrickmcmullan.com|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref> Bill Farrell,<ref name="bfanyc">{{cite web|url=http://bfanyc.com/people/michael-anthony-pegues|title=Michael Anthony Pegues|publisher=bfanyc.com|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref> Cojo "Art Juggernaut",<ref name="artsucks">{{cite web|url=http://www.artsucks.com/blog/2013/jan13/lambert-fine-arts-1-17-13.php|title=Decoded &#124; Lambert Fine Arts &#124; ArtSucks.com|publisher=artsucks.com|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref> and society photographer Annie Watt.<ref name="hamptons">{{cite web|url=http://www.hamptons.com/Gallery/1883/Steve-Forbes-Fetes-NYC-Mission-Society.html#.U2HlAv0U9dg|title=Steve Forbes Fetes NYC Mission Society &#124; Photos &#124; Hamptons|publisher=hamptons.com|accessdate=2014-10-31}}</ref>

